From a technical standpoint, it's not bad. There are a couple of minor lapses in tone here and there ( being somewhat colloquial and subjective descriptors in this context), but nothing that really breaks my immersion. The logs of the sites with populations of mayflies and their statuses struck me as right on the edge of providing too much filler for the sake of verisimilitude. It wasn't so much of a slog that I would necessarily fault that, but I can see how others might.

My main issue is that these are operating on essentially the same principle as Scranton anchors. In both things, reality has some sort of measurable, objective quality to it that can be used as a gauge and to inform predictable relationships. That's a concept that I reject because a) the idea that something like reality is somehow objectively measurable (and by extension,  or whatever) is completely ridiculous and b) it completely negates the sense of the uncanny and the inherently uncomprehendable that is one of the most important thematic elements of the site, at least to me.

By assigning clear values to what it means to be anomalous, to the point that we can now have convenient caches of indicator species that lets us know what's up, we've brought the anomalous back into the realm of science. For me as a reader, anytime that happens, I go from reading what is at its heart a magical realist narrative about the fantastic, to reading something boring and pedestrian. I know that other have different experiences, but to me, stuff like this saps interest and breaks immersion by introducing concepts that make absolutely no sense to me whatsoever.

I also don't care for the vagueness of the kicker at the end. With so little information about what the subject of the addenda are, you might as well have not even included them.







