I look at it like this:

Just because you know that something works, and that it can be used to observe something, doesn't mean you know why it works. And just because things are radically different, doesn't mean they can't be deeply connected.

One of the greatest breakthroughs of the early 1800s? The galvanometer, which allowed the precise measurement of these newly discovered  phenomena.

One of the greatest breakthroughs of the late 1800's? Figuring out why the hell galvanometers worked, why magnets screwed with them, and why they would sometimes measure currents when they weren't connected to anything: Magnetism and electricity were somehow related as a single  force.

Breakthrough of the early 1900's? Why they did weird things around those  things. Electromagnetism became electromagnetic radiation.

Breakthrough of the late 1900's? Finally figuring out that electromagnetic radiation is actually just one part of the electroweak force- which is also responsible for things like friction and the fact that your hand doesn't pass through your keyboard while you're typing. One fundamental force, many manifestations.





